{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585720"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:16:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:16:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15006"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15006"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.13,0.21,0.33,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66745"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15006"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52199"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5261"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"10942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66745"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAnti-staphylococcal penicillins were developed to combat penicillinase-producing bacteria. However, some resistant organisms have developed additional mechanisms to evade these antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes an anti-staphylococcal penicillin that is ineffective against methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amoxicillin","Penicillin G","Amoxicillin with clavulanic acid","Flucloxacillin","Penicillin V"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is an anti-staphylococcal penicillin that was developed to resist destruction by bacterial penicillinase enzymes. However, it remains ineffective against methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA) due to altered penicillin-binding proteins (PBP2a).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are not anti-staphylococcal penicillins:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is an aminopenicillin that is susceptible to penicillinase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPenicillin G\u003C/strong\u003E is a natural penicillin that is susceptible to penicillinase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin with clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E combines an aminopenicillin with a beta-lactamase inhibitor but is not classified as an anti-staphylococcal penicillin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPenicillin V\u003C/strong\u003E is an oral natural penicillin that is susceptible to penicillinase\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMRSA has developed resistance to all beta-lactam antibiotics through the production of PBP2a, which has a low affinity for beta-lactam binding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Flucloxacillin is an anti-staphylococcal penicillin that is resistant to penicillinase but not effective against methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA)","MRSA resistance occurs through altered penicillin-binding proteins (PBP2a), making it resistant to all beta-lactam antibiotics","Anti-staphylococcal penicillins were specifically developed to resist destruction by bacterial penicillinase enzymes"],"references":["Hauser, A. (